posts.cooked:
Hey, my team is planning to do a new robot for the off-season (2910), we are in advanced cad and we are almost finished. But there is a part that my team wants to manufacture that I’m pretty sure isn’t possible to manufacture with our resources and even if it’s possible it will take an unbearable amount of time and energy and it will be a complete waste. I will be happy if someone can give us advice about this part and tell if it’s even possible to manufacture.

Here are some informations about the part and our resources: ●our cnc is Laguna CNC ●the aluminum we will use for this part is 6061 ●we have ⅛inch, 4mm, 6mm heads for the cnc ●the part will be made from a 35mm aluminum plate ●we have special clamps to hold in a good position the plate in the different stages of the manufacturing IMG-20250706-WA0021 620×682 57.7 KB *the cad doesn’t have filets yet

posts.name: Tom Line
posts.cooked: Most of the laguna machines that I see are CNC routers.  How many axis is yours?  Is it a router, or an actual multi-axis CNC?

posts.name: Weston Bosworth
posts.cooked:
5gigalover:

we have ⅛, 4, 6 inch heads for the cnc

what does this mean? you have .125 endmills , and 4/6 inch facemills? did you mean to say 1/8, 1/4, and 1/6th endmills? what other tools do you have? any drills?

5gigalover:

*the cad doesn’t have filets yet

where are you planning on adding filets? to me, this part looks like you want to machine what’s in the picture, and hand deburr afterwards. adding cosmetic filets in the wrong places could drastically increase the difficulty of the part

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked:
Um.  May I suspect the designer is a 3D printing enthusiast?

Fixturing is going to be quite a challenge.  I think you need to cut into all six faces.

On a router you will need to start with "make a fixture that can repeatably orient and secure your part in all required orientations ".  That would likely be easier on a mill…  but still do-able on a stiff router.

You should take a quick peek at Patrick’s video on making crazy parts for the SDS MK5.

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked:
Also, I would patrol this part for ways to simplify it!!!   If at ALL possible,  make at least one side flat and NOT needed milling operations into it.

The depth of cut on many features looks deep relative to the feature size.  That central hole needs a bigger end mill.  Carbide for sure, otherwise flexibility will kill your work…

posts.name: JamesCH95
posts.cooked: Drop it in an automated CNC quoting interface like protolabs or xometry. If there’s a serious issue it will let you know. You’ll also get a price for manufacturing the part. Then you can weigh the $ vs team hours decision in a quantifiable way.
Only 3 axis

posts.name: David | 8866 A | Manufacturing+Hardware
posts.cooked:
If you wanna do it using only a 3 axis machine, it would be possible although probably pretty difficult.

We have a Laguna CNC we use for robotics and I personally would not attempt this part on our machine.

If I had to do this part where I work, it would be super easy since we have high quality work holding systems, probes, and machines with 5 axis.

Not saying you can’t do it, however have you thought through exactly how you’d hold and indicate the part? If so I’d like to see your set up.

R.C:

I recommend uploading a copy of this part to onshape for people to look at in depth.

Also yeah having access to the CAD of the part via OnShape would help a lot when determining how to make this

posts.name: Logan de Laar
posts.cooked: By the look of it this is a non structural part and is only holding bearings. Considering the cnc you have, it would be very difficult to machine this piece. Possible, yes, but you would likely spend way too much time and money on it. I would recommend redesigning it to include 3d printed parts and metal together. You might even be able to print the entire part in a nylon carbon fiber.

posts.name: EricH
posts.cooked:
Logandelaar:

I would recommend redesigning it to include 3d printed parts and metal together.

If you’re willing to wait a bit and spend money… how about 3D printed metal?

There are places that will let you upload an STL file and, for a fee, you’ll have a metal part in your hands some reasonable time later. Usually for build season, “reasonable time” is 1/3 of build season, so it’s not convenient to do that, but if you’re doing an offseason build and you’ve got time, why not?
